  "text": "About 50-100 µl of cell suspension were transferred into a Petri dish having a glass coverslip as a bottom. After a few minutes to allow the cells to settle on the glass, the dish was perfused with standard external saline (140 mM NaCl, 5 mM KCl, 2 mM CaCl 2 , 1 mM MgCl 2 , 10 mM HEPES-NaOH, pH 7.2-7.3). The whole-cell configuration, with full contact between the cytosol and the solution inside the micropipette, was used to dialyse the cells with the pipette solution. Access resistance was~5 MΩ. The pipette solution contained 125 mM potassium-Lglutamate, 10 mM NaCl, 7 mM MgCl 2 , 7 mM EGTA, 1 mM Na 2 ATP, 10 mM HEPES-NaOH, 20 µM GTPγS (unless noted otherwise), pH 7.2-7.3, and no added CaCl 2 ([Ca 2ϩ ] i Ͻ10 nM, as measured with a Ca 2ϩ -sensitive electrode, with Fura-2, and as calculated using the computer program BAD v. 4.42; [CITATION_1] . PMA, α-np and staurosporine were added as described below. For high Ca 2ϩ concentration ([Ca 2ϩ ] i ϭ 1.5 µM, as measured with a Ca 2ϩ -sensitive electrode), the solution contained 4.5 mM CaCl 2 and 5 mM EGTA instead of 7 mM EGTA. [Mg 2ϩ ] free was estimated to be 3.8 mM at low [Ca 2ϩ ] i and 5.8 mM at high [Ca 2ϩ ] i . The osmolality of the external solution was adjusted with D(ϩ)glucose (Merck) to exceed that of the pipette solution by a few mOsmol. All experiments were done at room temperature. All values given are means Ϯ SEM of the indicated number of cells, unless noted otherwise.",
